 and Romance sources, The Mercenary Mediterranean explores this little-known and misunderstood history. Far from marking the triumph of toleration, Hussein Fancy argues, the alliance of Christian kings and Muslim soldiers depended on and reproduced ideas of religious difference. Their shared history represents a unique opportunity to reconsider the relation of medieval religion to politics, and to demonstrate how modern assumptions about this relationship have impeded our understanding of both past and present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aForeign enlistmentxHistoryxSpainxAragon. 0aForeign enlistmentzSpainzAragonxHistory. 0aMudéjareszSpainzAragonxHistory. 0aMudéjaresxHistoryxSpainxAragon. 0aMuslimsxHistoryx13th centuryxAfrica, North. 0aMuslimsxHistoryx13th centuryxSpainxAragon. 0aMuslimsxHistoryx14th centuryxAfrica, North. 0aMuslimsxHistoryx14th centuryxSpainxAragon. 0aMuslimszAfrica, NorthxHistoryy13th century. 0aMuslimszAfrica, NorthxHistoryy14th century. 0aMuslimszSpainzAragonxHistoryy13th century. 0aMuslimszSpainzAragonxHistoryy14th century. 0aSoldiers of fortunexHistoryx13th centuryxSpainxAragon. 0aSoldiers of fortunexHistoryx14th centuryxSpainxAragon. 0aSoldiers of fortunezSpainzAragonxHistoryy13th century. 0aSoldiers of fortunezSpainzAragonxHistoryy14th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aaragon, muslim, islam, mercenaries, war, violence, religion, sovereignty, granada, christianity, 13th, 14th, arabic, latin, romance, religious difference, politics, history, nonfiction, soldiers of fortune, foreign enlistment, spain, mudejares, north africa, medieval, secularism, crusade, conquest, jihad, interfaith, identity, faith, empire, mediterranean, iberia, jenets.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity 